\u001b[1mDIARY\u001b[21m

\u001b[1mNAME\u001b[21m
	diary - print events from diary in the coming week

\u001b[1mOPTIONS\u001b[21m
	-a, --add
		Enter an interactive mode to add a new event to the diary.

	-d, --delete \x1B[3mnum\x1B[23m
		Remove events from the diary within \x1B[3mnum\x1B[23m days of today's date.
	 	\x1B[3mnum\x1B[23m must be an integer (0 for events occurring today) and there should
	 	be a space between it and the option specifier. A confirmation dialogue
	 	will be shown with the events to be deleted.

	\x1B[3mnum\x1B[23m
		Print events from diary within \x1B[3mnum\x1B[23m days of today's date.
	 	\x1B[3mnum\x1B[23m must be an integer (0 for events occurring today).

	-h, --help
		Display this message.

	-s, --save
		Save all diary events in a human readable format to the text file 
		\x1B[3mSCRIPT_DIR/saved_diary\x1B[23m (see setup below).
		If this file already exists, a number will be appended prior to saving.

	-v, --version
		Print the version of the program.

\u001b[1mSETUP\u001b[21m
- Ensure diary.py, events.json and usage are in the same directory.
- Create a bash alias by adding the following line to your ~/.bashrc
alias diary="python SCRIPT_DIR/diary.py"
(Otherwise 'python SCRIPT_DIR/diary.py' must be used to run the program).
Here SCRIPT_DIR must be entered \033[1mexplicitly\033[0m and python replaced with python3 if appropriate.
